Environment-climate: for a European New Deal
BRUSSELS - As in European capitals, the "Green New Deal" is on everyone's lips, echoing the visionary economic program launched by President Franklin D. Roosevelt in 1933.
But this time, it's the environment and the climate that's at issue.
And Europe is the continent where we can and where we must act.
The European Union's commitment to these issues is not new: we have a joint programme since 1972.
Later in 2005, the EU established its first emissions trading system, which remains the world's first CO2 market.
And in 2015, the EU played a driving role in the negotiation of the Paris Agreement, by committing to reduce its own greenhouse gas emissions by 40% (base: 1990 levels).
But these measures, despite their importance, are not enough to meet the challenges facing the world today.
Rising temperatures could lead to the complete disappearance of Arctic ice by 2050.
Bees and many other insects are dying out, as microplastic pollution is omnipresent in our environment.
And victims of respiratory diseases become more numerous as air pollution worsens.
We have reasons to remain optimistic nonetheless.
Let's see these people, growing in numbers day by day, ready to take action to challenge their lifestyles. Like these students and entire families descending into the streets of Stockholm, Prague, Brussels, and Milan every Thursday!
Businesses are also engaging, seeing the unmatched economic potential of a green economy.
But it is often the politicians and policymakers, at the national as well as the European level, who lack ambition too frequently.
We have a window of opportunity to act. Let's seize it.
And let us make a green Europe our top political priority for the years to come, centred on three key areas.
Firstly, Europe must become a carbon-neutral economy by 2050.
If we want to limit the warming of the planet to 1.5°C, we have no other option: the European Union's net carbon dioxide emissions must be brought to zero by the middle of the century.
Together, we can massively invest in the future of our mobility, energy-efficient buildings, and renewable energies, as well as key technologies such as hydrogen batteries, new generations of solar panels and green chemistry.
Together, we must also apply strict CO2 emissions limits to new private cars, public transport, and maritime and air commercial transport.
And by working closely with our automotive industry, we can make Europe the first continent for electric vehicles by 2030.
Secondly, Europe must play a major role in the responsible use of resources and become a genuine circular economy that is waste-efficient.
Every year, 8 billion tonnes of materials are converted into energy or products in the European Union.
But only 0.6 billion tons come from recycling.
We must do much better, which will require us to focus on four aspects: food waste and bioeconomy, textiles, construction and rapidly evolving consumer goods.
Let's get to work as of today, by launching for example an European initiative to fight against planned obsolescence of domestic appliances and electronic devices, and by abolishing plastics from our value chains.
Thirdly, we must do much more to protect biodiversity.
According to the WWF, wild species populations have declined by about 60% worldwide since 1970.
The United Nations biodiversity conference, which will be held in Beijing next year, will be decisive.
Once again, the EU must show the way.
We must strengthen EU legislation on species protection and put an ambitious plan on the table for the blue economy and the preservation of our seas.
We must also launch a genuine debate with our farmers (not against them!) on the revision of our standards and the modernization of the Common Agricultural Policy to support this green transition.
But these massive construction projects that await us, we will not be able to accomplish them if the same – and the most vulnerable – ones are still asked to bear the costs.
All measures considered will therefore have to be designed above all to minimize social costs.
At the same time, we have to start working with our partners today for international cooperation, fighting against unfair competition.
Because having strict European rules on pesticides or forestry management means nothing if our imported food and wood are produced without respecting sustainability criteria.
These three projects could become the pillars of a Sustainability Pact at the heart of the EU's new political cycle.
Because we are in a situation of acute ecological debt, it would be more than justified that the stability and growth pact, which applies to the public finances of member states, finds an equivalent for green goals of a green Europe !
To achieve its objectives, this Sustainability Pact will require coordinated action across all areas: climate, trade, taxation, agriculture, and innovation.
The EU must not be afraid to use its regulatory powers, for example: expanding the scope of legislation on ecodesign and "extended producer responsibility" for products on the market could greatly stimulate innovation in favour of the environment.
Massive investments will also be required.
The European Commission estimates that the EU will need an additional 180 billion euros of investment each year to meet its commitments under the Paris Agreement.
It's a achievable goal.
The European Investment Bank is already the largest multilateral climate-focused financier.
And the new EU budget and its investment plan, making the best use of private sector investments, could yet further strengthen the Union's power of action.
The financial sector will have to play a fundamental role: thanks to the disclosure of climate-related financial information, we can encourage the world's largest financial institutions, such as the Norwegian sovereign fund and BlackRock, to adopt a long-term view and avoid what former Bank of England Governor Mark Carney called the "tragedy of the horizon".
Finally, although some member states may see it as a risky project, we must hold a debate on taxation, but also on subsidies applied to fossil fuels. In short, on the integration of sustainability into public spending.
Behind these construction sites, these projects, the key lies in the method. For this "Green New Deal" to bear fruit, we must define ambitious short-term and long-term "missions" that have a real social resonance.
Together with the Member States and the European Parliament, we must determine a common roadmap and hold in-depth discussions, just as we will with our regions, our cities, businesses, trade unions and civil society.
All of this cannot be done overnight.
But we can no longer shut our eyes and hold our breath to escape the reality of our environment.
It is already very late to launch a "European Green New Deal." But it's not too late.
Let's not miss this new opportunity!
